1
00:00:14,584 --> 00:00:16,667
My name is Aladdin Khaled Ahmad

2
00:00:17,209 --> 00:00:18,876
I am from the Nabi Jirjis area

3
00:00:19,167 --> 00:00:21,209
I was born in 1973

4
00:00:22,709 --> 00:00:27,292
ISIS detained me over a medicines case

5
00:00:29,334 --> 00:00:33,167
I stayed in this place 28 days

6
00:00:34,542 --> 00:00:36,959
And 10 days in another place

7
00:00:43,125 --> 00:00:47,626
The medicines were for chronic illnesses

8
00:00:47,834 --> 00:00:49,083
They were not sold in pharmacies

9
00:00:49,876 --> 00:00:52,500
When they exceeded what the recipients needed

10
00:00:52,584 --> 00:00:54,959
They brought them to me, knowing I distributed to those in need

11
00:00:57,751 --> 00:00:59,751
Things like that

12
00:01:02,250 --> 00:01:03,417
I was under surveillance

13
00:01:03,667 --> 00:01:05,209
I felt I was being watched

14
00:01:05,709 --> 00:01:09,042
Because they were sending women to my store

15
00:01:10,834 --> 00:01:14,834
For medicines, and I gave injections to people for free

16
00:01:16,792 --> 00:01:19,959
Interviewer: Were the women they sent from among their members?

17
00:01:19,959 --> 00:01:21,918
Yes, members of ISIS

18
00:01:22,834 --> 00:01:25,792
Interviewer: Did you learn that from them, or later?

19
00:01:25,918 --> 00:01:26,918
I learned later

20
00:01:27,876 --> 00:01:30,918
After they detained me

21
00:01:32,834 --> 00:01:36,417
I only had a feeling that they were the ones sending them

22
00:01:37,459 --> 00:01:39,667
ISIS, and that was why I was detained

23
00:01:39,918 --> 00:01:42,167
Interviewer: What was the source of the medicines that came to you?

24
00:01:42,167 --> 00:01:44,167
It was from people who had more than they needed

25
00:01:44,209 --> 00:01:46,167
Yes, from people who wanted to do good

26
00:01:46,292 --> 00:01:48,500
Interviewer: Were there people who bought medicines

27
00:01:48,542 --> 00:01:51,042
Interviewer: And brought them to you seeking a reward for that?
Witness: Yes

28
00:01:51,626 --> 00:01:53,626
Interviewer: Did that happen with you?
Witness: Yes, it happened

29
00:01:54,751 --> 00:01:57,834
I used to work in a pharmacy

30
00:01:58,459 --> 00:01:59,959
So people in the area knew me

31
00:02:00,828 --> 00:02:03,083
They told anyone who wanted to donate, Take it to Abu Abd al-Rahman

32
00:02:03,125 --> 00:02:04,834
He is a man who does good for people

33
00:02:05,250 --> 00:02:07,584
So this was a trust I passed on seeking reward

34
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,918
I wanted to do good—I did not sell them

35
00:02:15,584 --> 00:02:16,626
I was in the store

36
00:02:18,083 --> 00:02:19,209
Two people came to me

37
00:02:19,959 --> 00:02:21,667
They said, Are you Aladdin? I said, Yes

38
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:26,751
He said, Please come with us to the <i>Hisba</i> [morality police]

39
00:02:28,334 --> 00:02:29,375
I said, What is the matter?

40
00:02:29,459 --> 00:02:31,584
They said, We want to ask you some questions

41
00:02:32,417 --> 00:02:34,751
They took me and brought me to this place

42
00:02:37,042 --> 00:02:38,167
They interrogated me

43
00:02:40,584 --> 00:02:43,542
When they brought me in, I was terrified, afraid

44
00:02:43,834 --> 00:02:46,918
Because their hands were stained with the blood of innocent people

45
00:02:46,959 --> 00:02:50,792
Now I would become one of those people

46
00:02:54,417 --> 00:02:57,667
Interviewer: The two people who brought you here

47
00:02:57,792 --> 00:02:59,709
Can you describe their appearance?

48
00:02:59,709 --> 00:03:03,042
And how old were they? What was their appearance?

49
00:03:03,542 --> 00:03:06,918
Were they from Mosul, based on the accent they spoke to you with?

50
00:03:07,209 --> 00:03:09,792
Or were they from the outskirts of Mosul, or from other provinces?

51
00:03:09,792 --> 00:03:11,459
Or were they of other Arab nationalities?

52
00:03:12,459 --> 00:03:13,584
They were from different backgrounds

53
00:03:13,626 --> 00:03:18,334
But the two who came to me—one was from Hadar and the other from Mosul.

54
00:03:19,584 --> 00:03:21,667
So their dialect was the Moslawi dialect

55
00:03:22,167 --> 00:03:23,375
They worked in the <i>Hisba</i>

56
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:25,584
Interviewer: Approximately how old were they?

57
00:03:26,959 --> 00:03:29,918
About 40 or 45 years old

58
00:03:30,876 --> 00:03:33,375
Yes, the two who took me

59
00:03:33,959 --> 00:03:35,417
Interviewer: How did they treat you from the moment they took you...

60
00:03:35,417 --> 00:03:36,709
until they brought you to the prison?

61
00:03:37,542 --> 00:03:39,626
Very normally

62
00:03:39,792 --> 00:03:42,375
They didn’t talk to me in front of people

63
00:03:42,626 --> 00:03:45,250
They brought me and led me in here

64
00:03:45,834 --> 00:03:46,876
And they interrogated me

65
00:03:47,083 --> 00:03:49,209
Interviewer: Did they bring you on foot or by car?
Witness: No, on foot

66
00:03:50,042 --> 00:03:52,834
Because the distance is short, about 10 minutes on foot

67
00:03:53,626 --> 00:03:55,250
Interviewer: Was one of them holding you?

68
00:03:55,292 --> 00:03:57,876
Or were you handcuffed?

69
00:03:58,125 --> 00:04:01,667
No, I walked in front of them and they were behind me, armed

70
00:04:02,709 --> 00:04:05,626
Interviewer: So they escorted you without anyone holding you

71
00:04:05,709 --> 00:04:07,125
No, no, they didn’t do anything to me

72
00:04:07,417 --> 00:04:09,042
They just told me they wanted to ask me questions

73
00:04:09,584 --> 00:04:12,209
Interviewer: When they took you to the prison gate

74
00:04:12,334 --> 00:04:13,584
Did those same men go in with you?

75
00:04:13,626 --> 00:04:15,334
Or did they hand you over to other people?

76
00:04:15,542 --> 00:04:18,042
They brought me here and then handed me over to other people

77
00:04:22,542 --> 00:04:25,292
When I came, I didn’t think this was a prison

78
00:04:25,334 --> 00:04:27,584
I told myself they would ask me questions

79
00:04:28,042 --> 00:04:30,667
And when they’d finished, I would leave

80
00:04:31,250 --> 00:04:34,542
But I was surprised that after they’d asked me questions, they detained me

81
00:04:35,209 --> 00:04:37,500
Interviewer: Since you are from this area

82
00:04:37,918 --> 00:04:39,459
What was this place before?

83
00:04:40,250 --> 00:04:41,334
This place used to be a church

84
00:04:42,292 --> 00:04:44,125
Interviewer: Do you remember having come in here before?

85
00:04:44,125 --> 00:04:46,584
When the Christians were present here?

86
00:04:46,584 --> 00:04:49,125
Yes, I entered this place many times

87
00:04:49,125 --> 00:04:51,125
There was a cemetery there

88
00:04:52,125 --> 00:04:53,250
It had graves

89
00:04:53,334 --> 00:04:56,125
We came in here when we were young

90
00:04:56,459 --> 00:04:58,959
We used to come here in the 80s and 90s

91
00:04:59,542 --> 00:05:02,584
We came as families—us and the Christians

92
00:05:04,334 --> 00:05:08,083
Interviewer: Aside from being neighbors with the Christians in the area

93
00:05:08,375 --> 00:05:10,417
Did you have special relationships, like friendships, with Christians?

94
00:05:10,459 --> 00:05:15,209
Which made you come to this place?

95
00:05:15,334 --> 00:05:18,834
Yes, they know I have many relationships with Christians

96
00:05:19,209 --> 00:05:26,125
For that reason, I imagine they asked me who was a priest, and who was in this church

97
00:05:26,375 --> 00:05:30,626
And in the other church, and who lived in the archbishopric

98
00:05:32,209 --> 00:05:34,584
Interviewer: When they first brought you into this place

99
00:05:34,626 --> 00:05:39,751
Into this entrance—which is the entrance to the church or to the prison itself

100
00:05:40,292 --> 00:05:42,417
What was there at the beginning?

101
00:05:42,667 --> 00:05:43,876
How did they treat you?

102
00:05:43,918 --> 00:05:46,042
And how did they treat your belongings?

103
00:05:46,459 --> 00:05:49,250
Did they deal with you when they took information from you?

104
00:05:49,250 --> 00:05:50,751
How was it?

105
00:05:51,334 --> 00:05:53,083
They took information from me

106
00:05:53,250 --> 00:05:54,834
Interviewer: What information did they take from you?

107
00:05:56,334 --> 00:05:59,125
I told you, they asked me about people

108
00:05:59,792 --> 00:06:03,209
What do you know about the Christians who were in this area?

109
00:06:03,209 --> 00:06:05,667
Interviewer: Was this when you arrived?
Witness: Yes

110
00:06:05,751 --> 00:06:07,584
Interviewer: When they took your belongings

111
00:06:07,751 --> 00:06:09,959
Interviewer: Did they enter your name into the computer?
Witness: Yes

112
00:06:09,959 --> 00:06:11,250
Interviewer: Did they fill out a form?

113
00:06:11,292 --> 00:06:12,876
Yes, they took my personal information

114
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:19,125
My full name, and what do you do? What is your job?

115
00:06:20,792 --> 00:06:23,959
What are your relations with people here in the area?

116
00:06:24,375 --> 00:06:26,000
Who do you know of the Christians?

117
00:06:27,167 --> 00:06:29,000
They asked me about all these things

118
00:06:29,375 --> 00:06:31,042
Interviewer: After they took your belongings

119
00:06:31,083 --> 00:06:32,083
Where did they take you?

120
00:06:33,042 --> 00:06:34,834
They took me and we entered the hall

121
00:06:36,375 --> 00:06:37,959
They interrogated me

122
00:06:39,334 --> 00:06:41,334
And that coincided with prayer time

123
00:06:41,834 --> 00:06:44,250
So I prayed two cycles as sunna

124
00:06:45,459 --> 00:06:46,792
After that I prayed the noon prayer

125
00:06:47,626 --> 00:06:49,751
In the archbishopric, then they took me back

126
00:06:50,459 --> 00:06:52,250
After they took me back they took me to the detention place

127
00:06:52,250 --> 00:06:53,250
To the prison upstairs

128
00:06:53,792 --> 00:06:55,584
I stayed upstairs for 28 days

129
00:07:00,292 --> 00:07:02,584
Interviewer: In the first moments of entering the room

130
00:07:02,626 --> 00:07:04,876
Tell me what was in your mind

131
00:07:05,167 --> 00:07:09,417
I thought they were going to execute me

132
00:07:11,626 --> 00:07:12,709
That is what I felt

133
00:07:14,125 --> 00:07:15,709
It was all terror and fear

134
00:07:16,876 --> 00:07:20,042
Because every little while you hear they took someone

135
00:07:20,834 --> 00:07:24,334
He might be a policeman for example, and they kill him

136
00:07:24,334 --> 00:07:26,250
Another for something else, for many reasons

137
00:07:27,250 --> 00:07:30,542
So I thought I would be one of the victims and be killed

138
00:07:30,959 --> 00:07:33,834
I imagined I would die like them

139
00:07:34,918 --> 00:07:37,542
Interviewer: How many people were with you in this room?

140
00:07:38,083 --> 00:07:40,292
At first I was alone

141
00:07:40,584 --> 00:07:43,209
Then a boy named Edmond came in

142
00:07:44,083 --> 00:07:46,042
A Christian, as if he had converted to Islam

143
00:07:46,667 --> 00:07:47,709
He stayed two days with me

144
00:07:48,792 --> 00:07:52,959
Later on every two or three days they would bring one or two

145
00:07:52,959 --> 00:07:58,417
He would sit two or three hours then they would transfer him

146
00:07:59,125 --> 00:08:01,584
Interviewer: Regarding the person you mentioned

147
00:08:01,626 --> 00:08:03,459
Edmond the Christian

148
00:08:04,083 --> 00:08:06,792
How did they treat him?

149
00:08:07,083 --> 00:08:08,792
Their treatment was good

150
00:08:09,792 --> 00:08:11,709
Interviewer: Didn’t you learn what his charge was?

151
00:08:11,709 --> 00:08:14,334
Since he was asked to surrender

152
00:08:14,334 --> 00:08:15,626
And he did, why arrest him?

153
00:08:16,167 --> 00:08:17,250
I was afraid to ask him

154
00:08:18,083 --> 00:08:19,834
Interviewer: Didn’t you talk about this?

155
00:08:19,876 --> 00:08:24,125
I was afraid because they listened to us through the windows

156
00:08:24,292 --> 00:08:27,959
They walked around the yard, so we were scared to talk

157
00:08:28,959 --> 00:08:31,751
Interviewer: Didn’t he try to ask you or talk with you?

158
00:08:31,792 --> 00:08:33,334
No, he didn’t ask me

159
00:08:34,083 --> 00:08:37,626
Interviewer: Did he show signs of torture?

160
00:08:37,918 --> 00:08:40,876
No, no, he didn’t show any signs of torture

161
00:08:41,125 --> 00:08:43,334
Interviewer: Didn’t they use any means of torture on him?

162
00:08:43,375 --> 00:08:45,500
No, he stayed two days with me

163
00:08:46,042 --> 00:08:48,083
Then they transferred him, and I don’t know where they took him

164
00:08:48,918 --> 00:08:49,918
Interviewer: Where was he from?

165
00:08:51,667 --> 00:08:54,959
I asked him, Are you from Mosul? He said, Yes

166
00:08:55,542 --> 00:08:59,167
I still remember he was from the Aden neighborhood

167
00:08:59,209 --> 00:09:01,375
He told me he lived in the Aden neighborhood

168
00:09:02,417 --> 00:09:04,959
And his family had all fled to Erbil

169
00:09:06,042 --> 00:09:07,209
And he had stayed here alone

170
00:09:07,542 --> 00:09:09,417
Interviewer: Didn’t you ask him why he’d stayed?

171
00:09:09,834 --> 00:09:12,292
I told you I was afraid to ask him

172
00:09:13,834 --> 00:09:15,209
I was afraid to ask him

173
00:09:15,334 --> 00:09:17,792
Because it’s possible he was with them

174
00:09:18,792 --> 00:09:20,709
Interviewer: So you stayed here 28 days

175
00:09:20,876 --> 00:09:23,083
And most of the time you were alone

176
00:09:23,125 --> 00:09:25,876
Interviewer: In this room or cell
Witness: Yes

177
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:27,876
Interviewer: How did you spend your time here?

178
00:09:28,626 --> 00:09:33,334
My time was harsh, a day felt like a year

179
00:09:35,250 --> 00:09:39,209
Interviewer: Didn’t they leave you something specific to use?

180
00:09:39,250 --> 00:09:42,250
Like prayers, since you were so close to death

181
00:09:42,500 --> 00:09:45,334
Interviewer: Were there Qurans in the prison?
Witness: Yes

182
00:09:45,709 --> 00:09:48,042
Interviewer: You mean they allowed them?
Witness: Yes, yes

183
00:09:48,083 --> 00:09:50,751
I had a Quran to read and I prayed normally

184
00:09:52,709 --> 00:09:55,500
I made <i>duaa</i> [supplication] and prayed

185
00:09:55,542 --> 00:09:58,834
I fulfilled my duty of worshipping God Almighty

186
00:10:00,584 --> 00:10:04,250
I prayed to God to free me, to let me out and get rid of them

187
00:10:05,209 --> 00:10:06,375
Interviewer: How did you spend the night?

188
00:10:06,959 --> 00:10:08,125
I spent it terrified

189
00:10:09,542 --> 00:10:10,584
It was all horror and fear

190
00:10:10,918 --> 00:10:16,042
Interviewer: While you were in this room at night

191
00:10:16,667 --> 00:10:20,125
Did you imagine they would come to you?

192
00:10:20,167 --> 00:10:23,918
Yes, I imagined they would come to me

193
00:10:23,959 --> 00:10:25,709
Interviewer: Can you describe this state to us?

194
00:10:25,709 --> 00:10:29,209
I imagined it to myself

195
00:10:29,292 --> 00:10:31,292
I told myself that after 10 minutes

196
00:10:31,334 --> 00:10:33,584
Or after an hour or two or at midnight

197
00:10:34,125 --> 00:10:36,459
They would call me, take me, and execute me

198
00:10:36,542 --> 00:10:38,000
Just like the others they executed

199
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:42,334
They planted horror and fear in my heart

200
00:10:42,834 --> 00:10:44,667
And this continues even now, as I talk to you

201
00:10:44,918 --> 00:10:49,042
As I speak with you now, I feel they are here

202
00:10:50,751 --> 00:10:53,375
Interviewer: Did you sleep very little?
Witness: Yes, very little

203
00:10:54,125 --> 00:10:55,667
Interviewer: Do you mean because of overthinking and fear?

204
00:10:55,667 --> 00:10:57,626
Yes, it is the thinking that exhausted me

205
00:10:57,667 --> 00:11:01,209
And I still take psychiatric medication to this day

206
00:11:01,459 --> 00:11:04,042
Interviewer: Given that you were alone in this place

207
00:11:05,292 --> 00:11:08,125
Did you find yourself not wanting to sleep out of fear

208
00:11:08,167 --> 00:11:09,334
That they would execute you while you slept?

209
00:11:09,375 --> 00:11:12,125
Yes, I felt afraid

210
00:11:13,083 --> 00:11:14,876
Interviewer: So you tried not to sleep?

211
00:11:14,918 --> 00:11:18,959
Yes, I tried not to sleep for fear they would kill me while I slept

212
00:11:20,792 --> 00:11:22,375
Interviewer: Was that imagination?

213
00:11:22,417 --> 00:11:25,375
Or did it reflect a real feeling inside you?

214
00:11:25,876 --> 00:11:27,292
It was a real feeling

215
00:11:28,792 --> 00:11:31,626
Interviewer: Have you heard of such a thing happening?

216
00:11:31,667 --> 00:11:33,334
Yes, they executed many people

217
00:11:34,751 --> 00:11:36,167
There’s the Khasfa sinkhole

218
00:11:36,209 --> 00:11:37,959
How many innocent people they threw into it

219
00:11:39,834 --> 00:11:41,918
More than 5,000, maybe up to 10,000

220
00:11:43,751 --> 00:11:48,083
Interviewer: You were alone, so surely you stayed silent the whole time

221
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:51,626
Did you have moments when you reflected during detention?

222
00:11:51,959 --> 00:11:55,375
Did you remember things and then sit and cry?

223
00:11:55,459 --> 00:12:00,667
Yes, I cried, I did not feel relief except after I’d cried

224
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:04,417
Interviewer: Did this happen often?
Witness: Yes, very often

225
00:12:05,584 --> 00:12:07,918
Very often, about once or twice daily

226
00:12:07,959 --> 00:12:09,626
I remembered my children and my wife

227
00:12:10,250 --> 00:12:12,209
I said to myself, I will not see them anymore

228
00:12:12,334 --> 00:12:17,209
Because they will execute me and my story will end

229
00:12:18,792 --> 00:12:22,042
And all my thoughts were of my children, my wife, and my home

230
00:12:23,167 --> 00:12:30,209
Interviewer: While you were in solitary confinement for 28 days

231
00:12:30,209 --> 00:12:33,125
Except for two nights when the Christian was with you

232
00:12:33,667 --> 00:12:36,417
How did they treat you throughout this period?

233
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,334
It was ordinary treatment

234
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:44,167
Interviewer: Was their speech harsh?

235
00:12:44,292 --> 00:12:47,209
There was shouting and so on

236
00:12:47,834 --> 00:12:50,918
Like, come here and go there, in a shouting tone

237
00:12:51,292 --> 00:12:52,584
And sometimes not

238
00:12:53,334 --> 00:12:55,834
They would tell me, for example, get up, Abu Abd al-Rahman, it is time for prayer

239
00:12:56,876 --> 00:13:00,417
Interviewer: Did this treatment differ from one jailer to another?

240
00:13:00,417 --> 00:13:01,751
Yes, it did, that is true

241
00:13:02,250 --> 00:13:04,500
Interviewer: So there was a jailer who respected you and called you Abu Abd al-Rahman?

242
00:13:04,542 --> 00:13:06,250
Yes, there were those who called me that

243
00:13:06,292 --> 00:13:07,709
Some of them respected me, and some did not

244
00:13:07,959 --> 00:13:10,083
Interviewer: Which jailers were more respectful to you?

245
00:13:10,125 --> 00:13:11,209
Those who were from Mosul

246
00:13:11,792 --> 00:13:13,584
Interviewer: Do you mean Mosul residents affiliated with them?

247
00:13:13,584 --> 00:13:15,334
Yes, from Mosul, they were respectful

248
00:13:16,083 --> 00:13:19,792
But the Arabs from the districts and subdistricts were not respectful

249
00:13:20,876 --> 00:13:22,959
They had all come out of prisons

250
00:13:24,042 --> 00:13:26,584
Their bodies were tattooed, and so on

251
00:13:27,375 --> 00:13:29,250
Interviewer: So they were hard on you?
Witness: Yes

252
00:13:29,542 --> 00:13:31,083
Yes, their speech was harsh toward people

253
00:13:32,542 --> 00:13:33,709
Because they are criminals

254
00:13:35,209 --> 00:13:38,167
Interviewer: Did you try to deal with them

255
00:13:38,167 --> 00:13:41,209
And ask them to bring you something from outside the prison?

256
00:13:41,500 --> 00:13:45,542
And if so, did they refuse?

257
00:13:45,834 --> 00:13:48,876
Did you try to give them a certain sum of money?

258
00:13:48,918 --> 00:13:53,959
So they would provide you a certain need or a comfort?

259
00:13:54,709 --> 00:13:59,292
Yes, sometimes I needed biscuits or other things from outside

260
00:13:59,584 --> 00:14:01,083
Or drinks and the like, and they would buy them for me

261
00:14:01,167 --> 00:14:05,209
I gave them money through the door slot to go, they would buy for me and return

262
00:14:06,292 --> 00:14:10,834
Interviewer: Wasn’t your money with the deposited belongings they took from you?

263
00:14:10,876 --> 00:14:13,209
The deposited belongings, which were my ID card and watch

264
00:14:13,375 --> 00:14:14,709
Were with them in the trailer

265
00:14:15,167 --> 00:14:16,250
Only the money was in my pocket

266
00:14:16,709 --> 00:14:18,876
Interviewer: Didn’t they take the money from you?
Witness: No, they didn’t take it

267
00:14:18,918 --> 00:14:20,417
I had money in my pocket

268
00:14:20,459 --> 00:14:22,334
When I needed something, I asked their permission

269
00:14:22,375 --> 00:14:24,959
And I said, sir, I want something

270
00:14:25,334 --> 00:14:28,250
Could someone go to the grocery and buy for me

271
00:14:28,667 --> 00:14:30,584
They would go, buy it for me, and bring it to me

272
00:14:31,125 --> 00:14:33,667
Interviewer: Didn’t he get annoyed with you when you asked him?

273
00:14:33,751 --> 00:14:36,167
I didn’t ask just anyone

274
00:14:36,209 --> 00:14:38,250
I asked the one who could tolerate me

275
00:14:40,709 --> 00:14:43,250
Interviewer: Did you feel comfortable with any of the jailers?

276
00:14:43,250 --> 00:14:44,751
In case a conversation happened between you

277
00:14:44,792 --> 00:14:47,459
No, no, because I was afraid of them

278
00:14:48,751 --> 00:14:52,500
Interviewer: Didn’t they try to reassure you, for example, and make you talk?

279
00:14:52,918 --> 00:14:58,792
No, frankly you will not feel reassurance with them

280
00:14:59,334 --> 00:15:04,042
Interviewer: Since you were in solitary, did you have a sense...

281
00:15:04,292 --> 00:15:07,959
Of the people they brought for several hours, meaning for a short time?

282
00:15:08,292 --> 00:15:11,459
Did they send in one of their members as a spy?

283
00:15:11,751 --> 00:15:15,459
Or did they assign people to question you or interrogate you inside?

284
00:15:15,751 --> 00:15:17,709
Sometimes I felt that

285
00:15:17,918 --> 00:15:21,334
I said to myself it is possible they would send one of the prisoners

286
00:15:21,334 --> 00:15:25,542
To lure me with his questions, and I would answer them

287
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:29,292
I was careful of them

288
00:15:29,876 --> 00:15:34,167
Interviewer: Were there rooms next to you from which you heard voices?

289
00:15:34,292 --> 00:15:36,250
Yes, I heard voices from here

290
00:15:37,417 --> 00:15:38,792
There were some in the back

291
00:15:40,876 --> 00:15:42,709
And in Mar Yousef Church

292
00:15:42,751 --> 00:15:45,417
But we did not hear their voices because they were a bit far

293
00:15:46,500 --> 00:15:47,751
They would bring them here

294
00:15:47,792 --> 00:15:51,500
When they whipped here, I heard the sound

295
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:55,792
They would bring whoever had prayer beads, or the like

296
00:15:55,834 --> 00:15:57,500
They held them accountable by flogging them here

297
00:15:58,042 --> 00:16:00,125
Whoever they caught because of cigarettes

298
00:16:00,876 --> 00:16:03,167
Or because of a satellite dish

299
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,209
They would punish them here, flogging them

300
00:16:07,792 --> 00:16:10,459
Interviewer: Okay, regardless of the flogging that happened during the day

301
00:16:10,751 --> 00:16:12,959
Did you hear sounds of torture at night?

302
00:16:13,959 --> 00:16:16,542
Interviewer: Like screams from prisoners, for example? Witness:
Yes, a little

303
00:16:17,292 --> 00:16:18,500
Interviewer: What were those sounds like?

304
00:16:20,042 --> 00:16:24,250
When they caught someone who worked in the police

305
00:16:24,250 --> 00:16:27,042
Or in the National Guard, for example, or in the army

306
00:16:28,250 --> 00:16:30,167
They would bring him in, ISIS’s security group

307
00:16:31,959 --> 00:16:35,167
From his screaming, it was clear they were beating him

308
00:16:35,667 --> 00:16:37,709
Because we heard the sound from the window

309
00:16:40,125 --> 00:16:42,792
Interviewer: Do you mean you didn’t see anyone being tortured?

310
00:16:42,792 --> 00:16:45,042
Interviewer: And you, were you not tortured in this prison?
Witness: No

311
00:16:46,125 --> 00:16:47,542
Interviewer: So only the sounds you heard…

312
00:16:47,584 --> 00:16:50,792
No, I didn’t see anything, they didn’t take me anywhere

313
00:16:55,626 --> 00:17:00,876
Rice and broth, they brought it ready in foam plates

314
00:17:01,375 --> 00:17:04,709
In the morning they brought us tahini and <i>sammoun</i> [bread roll]

315
00:17:04,751 --> 00:17:07,209
And sometimes they brought pieces of cheese with it

316
00:17:08,042 --> 00:17:10,626
That was in the morning, and at night they brought dinner

317
00:17:11,918 --> 00:17:14,334
Interviewer: Did they bring rice and broth daily?

318
00:17:15,375 --> 00:17:19,375
They varied it—it wasn’t the same food every day

319
00:17:20,209 --> 00:17:22,876
Interviewer: How many pieces of <i>sammoun</i> did they bring per day? Witness: Two in the morning

320
00:17:23,876 --> 00:17:28,626
At noon, one piece with a plate of rice and a cup of broth

321
00:17:29,167 --> 00:17:31,334
Interviewer: So they didn’t mix them together?
Witness: No

322
00:17:31,417 --> 00:17:32,417
Interviewer: And what about dinner?

323
00:17:32,667 --> 00:17:39,042
At dinner they sometimes brought <i>sammoun</i> and cooked chicken

324
00:17:40,042 --> 00:17:43,292
They gave us the leg of the chicken, or the wing, or something else

325
00:17:43,751 --> 00:17:46,292
Interviewer: Was the food enough?
Witness: Yes, it was enough

326
00:17:46,667 --> 00:17:50,959
When a person is in prison, he won’t crave food because of the worry

327
00:17:52,417 --> 00:17:54,876
Interviewer: Tell me honestly, was it enough? Witness: Yes, it was fine

328
00:17:55,542 --> 00:17:58,792
Interviewer: Was the quality good or bad? Witness: It was bad

329
00:18:01,209 --> 00:18:02,667
Interviewer: Did it come hot or cold?

330
00:18:02,918 --> 00:18:05,500
They brought it sometimes hot and at other times cold

331
00:18:05,959 --> 00:18:07,167
Meaning they brought it from far away

332
00:18:07,792 --> 00:18:11,500
Interviewer: Did it ever happen that they asked you what you like to eat?

333
00:18:11,542 --> 00:18:12,751
No, they didn’t ask me

334
00:18:14,083 --> 00:18:16,042
If a person wanted to buy food

335
00:18:17,459 --> 00:18:20,417
He would tell the jailer he craved food from outside

336
00:18:20,459 --> 00:18:21,500
Like kebab or something else

337
00:18:22,375 --> 00:18:24,125
When the market was open

338
00:18:25,167 --> 00:18:26,709
They would bring us from the guy called Hazem

339
00:18:26,709 --> 00:18:28,542
I twice asked to buy kebab from him

340
00:18:28,918 --> 00:18:30,125
Half a portion for one person

341
00:18:30,209 --> 00:18:31,500
Two skewers were enough for me, two pieces

342
00:18:32,500 --> 00:18:36,375
Interviewer: When you sent someone to buy food or what you needed

343
00:18:36,459 --> 00:18:39,209
Was the ISIS member you sent

344
00:18:39,542 --> 00:18:42,125
Bargaining with you to take an amount of money in return for that?

345
00:18:42,209 --> 00:18:45,626
I would tell him, If you’re hungry, get yourself food with mine

346
00:18:45,709 --> 00:18:47,125
And he would say to me, No, they don’t accept that

347
00:18:47,834 --> 00:18:52,083
Interviewer: Did he take an amount above the price of what he brought?

348
00:18:52,125 --> 00:18:53,459
No, he brought it at the same price

349
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:57,459
Interviewer: Didn’t it happen sometimes that someone asked you for a bribe?

350
00:18:57,459 --> 00:18:58,459
No, not at all

351
00:18:58,667 --> 00:19:00,792
Interviewer: For example to connect you with your family by a phone call

352
00:19:00,834 --> 00:19:03,250
No, but sometimes I would send him to my house

353
00:19:03,292 --> 00:19:04,542
To bring me medicine

354
00:19:04,918 --> 00:19:09,125
That happened twice—I sent him to bring me medicine

355
00:19:09,959 --> 00:19:11,292
And his name was Abu Taha

356
00:19:13,667 --> 00:19:14,667
Interviewer: Who is this Abu Taha?

357
00:19:14,959 --> 00:19:16,792
He is one of their members

358
00:19:17,250 --> 00:19:19,250
Interviewer: Did you know him before? Witness: No

359
00:19:20,125 --> 00:19:21,500
Interviewer: And when he did that

360
00:19:21,500 --> 00:19:23,500
By going to your house to bring you the medicine

361
00:19:23,500 --> 00:19:24,542
It was a kind act from him

362
00:19:24,584 --> 00:19:28,459
Interviewer: Did he do that on their orders or on his own?

363
00:19:28,500 --> 00:19:32,834
No, on his own. Wasn’t he the jailer responsible for the room?

364
00:19:32,876 --> 00:19:35,792
During his shift I would ask him to go, because he knew the house, it was nearby

365
00:19:36,209 --> 00:19:38,083
Anyone from the street could have gone to bring it for me

366
00:19:38,667 --> 00:19:42,000
I used Angised and Isordil, heart medications

367
00:19:42,083 --> 00:19:44,709
Interviewer: In this case, did your family know you were detained?

368
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:46,792
But they didn’t know in which place exactly

369
00:19:47,167 --> 00:19:49,167
Interviewer: So he didn’t tell them your location?
Witness: No, he didn’t tell them

370
00:19:49,584 --> 00:19:51,542
Interviewer: During your 28 days

371
00:19:51,626 --> 00:19:54,834
Did you need a doctor, or for a nurse to come to you?

372
00:19:54,876 --> 00:19:56,083
Did a doctor actually visit you?

373
00:19:56,083 --> 00:19:58,584
No, I know what I suffer from

374
00:19:59,209 --> 00:20:00,417
And the treatment I take

375
00:20:01,375 --> 00:20:02,959
Interviewer: Regardless of your knowledge of what you suffer from

376
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:05,834
Did their schedule include a doctor visiting you from time to time?

377
00:20:05,876 --> 00:20:08,626
Yes, they asked us if we needed a doctor

378
00:20:08,667 --> 00:20:09,709
So they could take us to him

379
00:20:10,250 --> 00:20:14,792
If you felt your blood pressure was high, for example, or something like that

380
00:20:15,584 --> 00:20:19,918
But I didn’t ask them for this

381
00:20:20,667 --> 00:20:23,459
Interviewer: You mean there was understanding of your health condition

382
00:20:23,459 --> 00:20:24,876
And special consideration for you

383
00:20:24,959 --> 00:20:25,959
Yes, they knew that

384
00:20:26,876 --> 00:20:28,167
Interviewer: Regarding the food

385
00:20:28,209 --> 00:20:32,209
Was there any kind that harmed you and they still brought it to you?

386
00:20:32,209 --> 00:20:34,209
Or did they not bring it to you because you told them it harmed you?

387
00:20:34,918 --> 00:20:37,334
No, the food they brought didn’t harm me

388
00:20:38,125 --> 00:20:40,459
If there was fat, I wouldn’t eat it

389
00:20:41,292 --> 00:20:43,626
For example, I would eat the bread and the chicken thigh

390
00:20:44,417 --> 00:20:45,459
And I wouldn’t eat the rest

391
00:20:45,459 --> 00:20:47,334
Because I suffered from high blood lipids, and until now

392
00:20:47,375 --> 00:20:49,709
Interviewer: Didn’t it happen one day that they asked you

393
00:20:49,751 --> 00:20:52,167
About this food, whether it was beneficial or harmful to you?

394
00:20:52,167 --> 00:20:54,167
And did they try to bring you something that would help you and not harm you?

395
00:20:54,209 --> 00:20:56,709
They asked me, and I told them this doesn’t harm me

396
00:20:57,459 --> 00:20:59,209
Interviewer: So they asked you?
Witness: Yes, they asked me

397
00:20:59,667 --> 00:21:02,959
Interviewer: Do you think you had some kind of special care in the prison?

398
00:21:03,417 --> 00:21:04,500
Not like the treatment of others

399
00:21:04,542 --> 00:21:07,042
Interviewer: Considering they placed you in a place by yourself

400
00:21:07,083 --> 00:21:08,375
It was like that somewhat

401
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:10,167
Interviewer: Was that because of your age?

402
00:21:10,167 --> 00:21:15,000
Or because they expected you would be with them and help them

403
00:21:15,042 --> 00:21:16,042
Yes, it was for that reason

404
00:21:17,167 --> 00:21:20,626
Meaning because they needed me, and they wanted me to join them

405
00:21:21,125 --> 00:21:23,709
This good treatment, they wanted from it in return

406
00:21:23,792 --> 00:21:28,042
To motivate you and urge you to join them

407
00:21:28,083 --> 00:21:29,167
Yes, it was like that

408
00:21:29,417 --> 00:21:31,918
Interviewer: Is that it?
Witness: Yes, I felt that

409
00:21:36,751 --> 00:21:40,792
In the morning when I woke up and wanted to go to the toilets

410
00:21:41,459 --> 00:21:45,542
They allowed me to go there to relieve myself and return

411
00:21:46,083 --> 00:21:49,751
And as for bathing, it was twice a week

412
00:21:50,584 --> 00:21:53,250
On Mondays and Thursdays we had the right to bathe

413
00:21:53,834 --> 00:21:57,083
And they gave us ten minutes or a quarter hour to bathe

414
00:21:57,959 --> 00:22:03,459
Interviewer: When you relieved yourself, did you do so comfortably?

415
00:22:03,459 --> 00:22:05,125
Or did you feel you were being watched?

416
00:22:07,751 --> 00:22:10,792
When I entered the toilets, I felt I was being watched

417
00:22:11,500 --> 00:22:14,000
Interviewer: And were you actually watched, or was it just a feeling?

418
00:22:14,042 --> 00:22:15,083
It was a feeling

419
00:22:15,125 --> 00:22:17,042
Interviewer: So you weren’t watched?
Witness: No, I wasn’t watched

420
00:22:17,042 --> 00:22:19,542
But it was my feeling because the toilets were adjacent to the prison

421
00:22:20,375 --> 00:22:25,042
It was next to the parking area, and the jailer stood outside next to the toilets

422
00:22:25,834 --> 00:22:28,709
Interviewer: Regarding cleanliness in the prison

423
00:22:28,751 --> 00:22:31,042
Did they give you cleaning supplies to clean the room?

424
00:22:31,083 --> 00:22:33,876
Yes, they gave us some

425
00:22:34,417 --> 00:22:36,042
Interviewer: Were they available regularly?

426
00:22:36,083 --> 00:22:39,000
Yes, available—they gave us Dettol and a bucket of water

427
00:22:40,375 --> 00:22:42,334
Every two days we wiped the room

428
00:22:43,042 --> 00:22:48,334
Interviewer: Was the cleaning time mandatory on a certain day?

429
00:22:48,459 --> 00:22:51,584
Every two days we had the task of cleaning the room

430
00:22:51,918 --> 00:22:53,083
We did the cleaning inside the room

431
00:22:54,042 --> 00:22:57,709
Interviewer: Was hot and cold water available in the showers?

432
00:22:57,709 --> 00:23:00,209
Yes, they heated the water for us to bathe with

433
00:23:00,250 --> 00:23:05,125
They gave us a bucket of water with about 50 liters of water

434
00:23:05,792 --> 00:23:09,417
We bathed with it—we had to finish within 10 minutes to a quarter hour

435
00:23:09,626 --> 00:23:12,209
Interviewer: Did they distribute underwear to you?
Witness: No

436
00:23:13,542 --> 00:23:15,709
Interviewer: Didn’t they give you other clothes?
Witness: No

437
00:23:17,125 --> 00:23:20,334
When I sent them to bring me the medicine

438
00:23:20,626 --> 00:23:24,709
My family sent me underwear and pajamas

439
00:23:25,834 --> 00:23:27,709
Interviewer: Was bringing them in normal?
Witness: Yes

440
00:23:28,626 --> 00:23:30,375
Interviewer: Did they not allow visits in the prison?

441
00:23:30,417 --> 00:23:34,292
No, they didn’t allow anyone to do that, and my family knew that

442
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:40,918
Interviewer: Okay, in these 38 days

443
00:23:40,959 --> 00:23:43,876
28 days in this prison and 10 days in another prison

444
00:23:44,292 --> 00:23:47,959
How many times did you go to interrogation and to the judge?
Witness: Twice

445
00:23:50,042 --> 00:23:53,542
Interviewer: And was the judge the same both times?

446
00:23:54,584 --> 00:23:58,834
No, they were different people in each interrogation

447
00:23:59,542 --> 00:24:01,959
Interviewer: So the first interrogation happened in the hall?
Witness: Here

448
00:24:01,959 --> 00:24:03,250
Interviewer: And where did the other one happen?

449
00:24:03,834 --> 00:24:05,834
It happened at the archdiocese

450
00:24:06,459 --> 00:24:08,542
Interviewer: What did he ask you about specifically at the archdiocese?

451
00:24:09,626 --> 00:24:12,042
He asked me about the matter of the medicines as well

452
00:24:13,042 --> 00:24:18,292
And as I told you, he asked me about the people present here

453
00:24:18,292 --> 00:24:21,584
Whom you know, and who was in this church

454
00:24:21,626 --> 00:24:29,292
And who the priest is, about his family, his children, and his brothers, and what you know

455
00:24:30,751 --> 00:24:34,250
And whom you know among the Christians who left

456
00:24:34,542 --> 00:24:36,709
I told him, All the Christians left—none remained

457
00:24:36,751 --> 00:24:38,959
Some remained who had converted to Islam

458
00:24:38,959 --> 00:24:40,709
Among them this Saadallah, the restaurant owner

459
00:24:41,667 --> 00:24:45,709
He converted to Islam out of fear, and stayed here

460
00:24:47,459 --> 00:24:51,125
Then he went to Baghdad and returned to his religion again

461
00:24:51,918 --> 00:24:57,584
Interviewer: Did they try to get information from you, not only about the Christians?

462
00:24:57,626 --> 00:25:00,876
But about their money, their houses, and their properties in the area

463
00:25:00,918 --> 00:25:06,709
And details about things they couldn’t know, for example

464
00:25:07,542 --> 00:25:10,918
They asked me about the graves of the Christians

465
00:25:11,375 --> 00:25:14,542
About the burial place of the priests

466
00:25:14,584 --> 00:25:15,959
I told them, In Mary Church

467
00:25:17,667 --> 00:25:21,209
The tomb is in the church in the Qasan area

468
00:25:21,375 --> 00:25:23,667
I know that because I participated with them, as they were my neighbors

469
00:25:23,959 --> 00:25:26,375
They have intelligence and information and know everything

470
00:25:26,417 --> 00:25:30,667
They know what the child playing in the street is doing

471
00:25:32,375 --> 00:25:34,959
Interviewer: Were you surprised by these questions?
Witness: Yes, of course I was surprised

472
00:25:36,626 --> 00:25:39,292
Interviewer: These questions they asked you that surprised you

473
00:25:41,417 --> 00:25:45,626
What did they leave you with exactly during the interrogation?

474
00:25:45,667 --> 00:25:49,042
I became fearful, terrified

475
00:25:49,834 --> 00:25:51,542
Because they frighten people

476
00:25:52,876 --> 00:25:55,250
Interviewer: Did they use threats with you during the interrogation?

477
00:25:56,042 --> 00:25:57,417
Yes, to some extent

478
00:25:58,375 --> 00:25:59,459
Interviewer: What did he say to you, for example?

479
00:26:00,626 --> 00:26:07,083
He said, Speak, Hajj, about what you know

480
00:26:07,792 --> 00:26:09,209
Better than us asking you

481
00:26:09,834 --> 00:26:12,209
So I told them what I had

482
00:26:12,792 --> 00:26:14,292
So that they wouldn’t be the ones asking me

483
00:26:15,292 --> 00:26:17,834
Interviewer: What did he ask you specifically?

484
00:26:18,792 --> 00:26:21,459
They asked me, What is your job?

485
00:26:21,542 --> 00:26:24,250
And who comes to you, and who sits with you?

486
00:26:24,542 --> 00:26:25,959
And what do you know about ISIS

487
00:26:26,751 --> 00:26:30,250
Out of fear I told them that ISIS is good

488
00:26:30,751 --> 00:26:33,417
And there’s nothing wrong with it, and you are an Islamic state

489
00:26:34,584 --> 00:26:35,626
Things like that

490
00:26:36,584 --> 00:26:40,125
And I was terrified of them

491
00:26:40,542 --> 00:26:43,667
Interviewer: From the questions they asked you

492
00:26:43,751 --> 00:26:46,375
It appears they knew many details about you

493
00:26:46,626 --> 00:26:53,000
Did they beat you or insult you while questioning you?

494
00:26:53,042 --> 00:26:55,042
Or did any of the members standing behind you

495
00:26:55,417 --> 00:27:01,417
Attempt to deal with you with a weapon or by using a sharp instrument?

496
00:27:01,459 --> 00:27:04,083
Or did anything specific happen during their interrogation of you?

497
00:27:04,751 --> 00:27:06,959
No, from when they took me to Mar Yousef Church

498
00:27:07,626 --> 00:27:11,209
I overstepped a little in speaking with them

499
00:27:12,209 --> 00:27:13,709
So one of them pushed me

500
00:27:14,083 --> 00:27:16,667
And I told you when I fell on the stairs

501
00:27:16,667 --> 00:27:18,959
Because there were stairs

502
00:27:19,584 --> 00:27:21,751
This fall still affects me

503
00:27:21,792 --> 00:27:24,042
I have pain in my back and legs

504
00:27:24,834 --> 00:27:28,792
Interviewer: What caused the problems during the conversation?

505
00:27:29,584 --> 00:27:31,584
Because they brought me in unjustly

506
00:27:33,834 --> 00:27:40,209
I mean, I hadn’t committed a crime to be imprisoned, or anything like that

507
00:27:40,792 --> 00:27:44,876
And I knew I had done nothing and that I was innocent

508
00:27:45,792 --> 00:27:47,542
When my imprisonment dragged on

509
00:27:48,584 --> 00:27:50,542
I asked them, What is the reason for my imprisonment?

510
00:27:51,209 --> 00:27:53,709
They told me, You know everything. But I didn't know anything

511
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:03,250
I had suspicions that they wanted me to work with them

512
00:28:04,500 --> 00:28:07,209
And I would not work with them, and I stayed that way, thank God

513
00:28:07,292 --> 00:28:09,751
Interviewer: Did they ask you to work with them directly?

514
00:28:09,876 --> 00:28:14,250
No, but through their questions it became clear they wanted me to work with them

515
00:28:14,584 --> 00:28:15,876
Interviewer: What did he say to you, for example?

516
00:28:16,292 --> 00:28:22,959
He said, For example, we have wounded people. Can you insert an IV cannula for them?

517
00:28:22,959 --> 00:28:24,125
Or give them injections

518
00:28:24,209 --> 00:28:27,292
I told them I don't have a license to do that, and I was afraid, and so on

519
00:28:27,792 --> 00:28:29,459
And that I had sworn not to give an injection to anyone

520
00:28:29,959 --> 00:28:34,959
Interviewer: So they asked you to help them according to your medical specialty?

521
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:38,292
Yes, but I didn't leave them any room for that and I didn't work with them

522
00:28:39,042 --> 00:28:42,083
Interviewer: So they didn’t ask you to join them and pledge allegiance directly?

523
00:28:42,083 --> 00:28:46,083
Yes, not directly

524
00:28:46,626 --> 00:28:49,125
I felt they wanted me to work with them

525
00:28:49,584 --> 00:28:51,500
But I didn't give them any room and I didn't work with them

526
00:28:51,876 --> 00:28:56,167
Interviewer: After they’d completed the interrogation with you in this hall inside this building

527
00:28:56,584 --> 00:28:58,125
Where did they take you after that?

528
00:28:58,709 --> 00:29:02,292
They took me to a holding house, which was the house of Raed Jobbo

529
00:29:02,792 --> 00:29:04,292
Which was basically a house used as a prison

530
00:29:05,250 --> 00:29:11,334
They put us into a religious course for 10 days

531
00:29:11,751 --> 00:29:13,334
After these 10 days

532
00:29:13,876 --> 00:29:19,209
My detention then totaled 38 days, then they released me

533
00:29:23,500 --> 00:29:26,375
I told you I stayed here 28 days

534
00:29:27,459 --> 00:29:31,459
Then they moved me to that house, which was also a prison

535
00:29:32,334 --> 00:29:33,709
I stayed there 10 days

536
00:29:34,667 --> 00:29:41,417
In those 10 days they put me in a course of religious instruction and <i>tawhid</i>

537
00:29:42,125 --> 00:29:43,959
When the 10 days ended they released us

538
00:29:45,417 --> 00:29:51,542
Interviewer: When they transferred you to the other prison and you stayed there 10 days

539
00:29:52,125 --> 00:29:55,542
Were you by yourself, or were you with a group?

540
00:29:55,667 --> 00:30:00,209
No, I was with a large group, more than 30 people, roughly

541
00:30:01,542 --> 00:30:03,292
Interviewer: Had those people been imprisoned for a long time?

542
00:30:04,918 --> 00:30:07,834
Some for 10 days, some stayed a month, others eight days

543
00:30:08,709 --> 00:30:10,250
It depended on each person's case

544
00:30:10,834 --> 00:30:13,500
Interviewer: Can you tell me the charges they were accused of?

545
00:30:13,959 --> 00:30:15,375
One of them because of birds

546
00:30:15,959 --> 00:30:17,334
And another because of cigarettes

547
00:30:18,584 --> 00:30:21,250
And another they caught while he was smuggling cigarettes in a car

548
00:30:22,584 --> 00:30:23,626
His name was Khalil

549
00:30:26,334 --> 00:30:30,375
Various charges, most for smoking

550
00:30:30,918 --> 00:30:34,709
Interviewer: Considering there was a group of people during those 10 days

551
00:30:34,751 --> 00:30:39,667
And you had come out of solitary to a prison with a group

552
00:30:39,876 --> 00:30:43,834
How were your relationships? And how did you spend your days and nights together?

553
00:30:43,876 --> 00:30:46,792
It was normal, we talked freely

554
00:30:47,584 --> 00:30:54,125
And when the time for the lessons came

555
00:30:54,167 --> 00:30:58,375
We went out and sat in the house courtyard. We sat in pairs, and they taught us

556
00:30:59,167 --> 00:31:03,626
Interviewer: In that prison where you stayed 10 days

557
00:31:03,834 --> 00:31:06,709
Interviewer: And you were 30 people?
Witness: Yes, more than 30

558
00:31:06,792 --> 00:31:10,876
Interviewer: What were their ages, roughly the youngest to the oldest?

559
00:31:11,834 --> 00:31:14,834
There were 18-year-olds, and there were 40-year-olds

560
00:31:15,959 --> 00:31:19,918
And there were 50-year-olds—there were various ages

561
00:31:20,751 --> 00:31:23,292
Interviewer: Because of this difference between ages, between young and old

562
00:31:23,292 --> 00:31:27,918
And because of differences in mindsets and backgrounds

563
00:31:27,959 --> 00:31:33,167
Were there quarrels or problems between them, or between one group and another, while you were there?

564
00:31:33,209 --> 00:31:37,959
No, no problems happened between the prisoners at all

565
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:44,209
On the contrary, we got along and liked each other

566
00:31:44,542 --> 00:31:45,792
Everyone helped each other

567
00:31:46,209 --> 00:31:49,959
If someone was hungry and had no food, another gave him some of his food

568
00:31:50,334 --> 00:31:51,334
We ate together, for example

569
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:56,500
If someone had a headache we gave him a painkiller tablet

570
00:31:57,209 --> 00:31:58,334
That was how it was

571
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:05,083
Interviewer: How did they treat you there as a group?

572
00:32:05,125 --> 00:32:07,292
When you were by yourself, you had special care

573
00:32:07,542 --> 00:32:09,626
Was the care the same there?

574
00:32:10,083 --> 00:32:11,542
Yes, there was care

575
00:32:11,626 --> 00:32:16,876
And they had a person there

576
00:32:20,417 --> 00:32:22,375
He was responsible for something like a pharmacy

577
00:32:23,584 --> 00:32:26,083
Meaning he was from ISIS

578
00:32:27,083 --> 00:32:29,751
He had a set of medicines that he gave to anyone suffering from something

579
00:32:29,792 --> 00:32:34,417
They had medications for headaches or heart conditions

580
00:32:36,125 --> 00:32:38,292
It was in the hallway, like a small pharmacy

581
00:32:39,167 --> 00:32:42,083
Interviewer: Were you allowed to move around inside there?

582
00:32:42,125 --> 00:32:43,709
It is a small house

583
00:32:44,250 --> 00:32:46,584
We wandered in its courtyard or in the room—nothing more than that

584
00:32:47,042 --> 00:32:49,083
Interviewer: Was it allowed to go out to the courtyard at any time?

585
00:32:49,125 --> 00:32:54,083
Yes, the room doors were open, and the house was fortified from the outside

586
00:32:55,375 --> 00:32:58,250
Interviewer: How many guards were there?
Witness: Five guards

587
00:32:59,334 --> 00:33:01,500
Interviewer: How did they treat you?

588
00:33:02,375 --> 00:33:03,792
It was fine, not bad

589
00:33:04,375 --> 00:33:07,125
Interviewer: Were their nationalities or accents those of Mosul locals and Bedouins?

590
00:33:07,167 --> 00:33:08,292
Or were they only from Mosul?

591
00:33:08,542 --> 00:33:13,584
They were mixed—two of them were from Diyala, as I recall

592
00:33:14,209 --> 00:33:17,334
And three were from the outskirts of Mosul

593
00:33:18,125 --> 00:33:20,626
Interviewer: Was the food there like it was here?

594
00:33:20,834 --> 00:33:23,375
Yes, they brought us the same food

595
00:33:24,834 --> 00:33:27,459
Interviewer: Was there any discrimination between one prisoner and another, or not?

596
00:33:27,459 --> 00:33:30,083
No, everyone was equal

597
00:33:30,834 --> 00:33:36,375
Interviewer: You said there was a small pharmacy

598
00:33:36,375 --> 00:33:38,751
Yes, it was small, for whoever needed a painkiller tablet

599
00:33:38,834 --> 00:33:42,167
Or, for example, someone with a sore throat, they gave him a capsule

600
00:33:43,751 --> 00:33:45,209
They dispensed the medicine for him normally

601
00:33:46,042 --> 00:33:49,626
Interviewer: This place is indeed a prison

602
00:33:49,751 --> 00:33:53,584
But as a prison, did you feel there was special care?

603
00:33:53,667 --> 00:33:57,083
Or was that, as you mentioned, because they needed

604
00:33:57,167 --> 00:34:01,792
To ask you and others to join them?

605
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:08,375
It was varied because each person had a different case

606
00:34:09,792 --> 00:34:12,042
Interviewer: Since you were now with a group of prisoners

607
00:34:12,083 --> 00:34:13,959
How did you spend your nights and days with them?

608
00:34:13,959 --> 00:34:15,626
It was normal—it was better than here

609
00:34:16,042 --> 00:34:21,250
Interviewer: Tell me about your life and the times you spent in the prison

610
00:34:21,292 --> 00:34:25,250
We used to talk most of the time

611
00:34:26,417 --> 00:34:31,792
We got to know each other and asked where people lived, for example

612
00:34:33,417 --> 00:34:36,709
And we talked about religion in case they were listening

613
00:34:37,250 --> 00:34:38,876
They would know we were talking about religion

614
00:34:40,125 --> 00:34:42,542
We talked about religious stories and such things

615
00:34:43,083 --> 00:34:44,125
We spent time like that

616
00:34:44,459 --> 00:34:47,751
Interviewer: Do you think there were spies among you from their personnel?

617
00:34:47,792 --> 00:34:52,167
Or did they bring in people who volunteered to act as spies and pass information

618
00:34:52,959 --> 00:34:54,834
I don't know—I don't think so

619
00:34:55,709 --> 00:34:59,918
I don't think any of their members were among the prisoners

620
00:35:01,709 --> 00:35:09,459
Do you remember particular stories that happened during your imprisonment there over the 10 days?

621
00:35:09,542 --> 00:35:11,792
Or a specific person's story you still remember

622
00:35:12,083 --> 00:35:15,000
Or a story that affected you that you still remember

623
00:35:15,042 --> 00:35:18,375
And it hurts when you remember it

624
00:35:18,626 --> 00:35:21,417
Or a case of a particular person that happened in front of you?

625
00:35:21,667 --> 00:35:23,667
Or a particular injustice?

626
00:35:24,083 --> 00:35:25,792
It was all injustice

627
00:35:27,584 --> 00:35:29,042
Because we were all unjustly imprisoned

628
00:35:30,250 --> 00:35:31,500
Can someone be imprisoned because of cigarettes?

629
00:35:32,125 --> 00:35:34,792
It was all injustice, like the one they brought because of cigarettes

630
00:35:34,834 --> 00:35:40,209
And the one they brought and flogged because he’d said a word outside to his friend

631
00:35:40,250 --> 00:35:41,751
Trivial things

632
00:35:42,834 --> 00:35:48,167
Interviewer: Weren't there any charges more serious than cigarettes?

633
00:35:48,542 --> 00:35:51,459
Or did they bring someone unjustly when he didn’t even have cigarettes?

634
00:35:52,584 --> 00:35:57,125
Most of them were family matters

635
00:35:57,792 --> 00:36:02,626
Meaning they would also bring someone who had a problem with his wife, or whose voice was loud

636
00:36:04,292 --> 00:36:06,083
Interviewer: They hear his voice and then bring him?

637
00:36:06,125 --> 00:36:08,083
Someone files a complaint against him

638
00:36:09,542 --> 00:36:12,250
Meaning they had operatives everywhere

639
00:36:13,167 --> 00:36:15,417
For example, they hear that someone blasphemed, so they bring him

640
00:36:16,125 --> 00:36:20,083
Or if someone blasphemes, they would behead him on the spot

641
00:36:22,042 --> 00:36:24,542
Interviewer: How did you spend your time in the prison?

642
00:36:25,375 --> 00:36:32,792
They gave us papers containing religious material to memorize

643
00:36:33,500 --> 00:36:38,292
Quranic verses and suras, and <i>tawhid</i> material to memorize

644
00:36:39,209 --> 00:36:42,209
And instruction, and such things

645
00:36:43,209 --> 00:36:44,709
Interviewer: Did you memorize them as lessons?

646
00:36:45,125 --> 00:36:46,584
Yes, they asked us in the morning when we woke up

647
00:36:48,626 --> 00:36:51,083
Interviewer: So lessons and homework?
Witness: Yes

648
00:36:51,584 --> 00:36:54,292
They gave us three or four pages of paper

649
00:36:55,292 --> 00:36:57,167
We memorized them and in the morning we answered their questions

650
00:36:57,167 --> 00:36:58,918
No one is unaware of these things

651
00:36:58,959 --> 00:37:02,459
Everyone knows the Ibrahimiyya prayers

652
00:37:02,500 --> 00:37:05,584
We all had them memorized

653
00:37:06,792 --> 00:37:09,375
Interviewer: So it was like a school
Witness: Yes, almost

654
00:37:10,042 --> 00:37:12,667
Interviewer: What kind of lessons were they?

655
00:37:12,709 --> 00:37:14,375
And who was the person who taught you?

656
00:37:14,417 --> 00:37:16,292
Was it the same person who came every time?

657
00:37:16,334 --> 00:37:18,542
Yes, it was the same person and his name was Abu Muhammad

658
00:37:19,876 --> 00:37:22,542
Interviewer: Was it the same one who came daily? Didn't someone else come?

659
00:37:22,584 --> 00:37:23,626
No, the same one came

660
00:37:24,167 --> 00:37:26,417
Interviewer: Can you describe to me what he looked like?

661
00:37:26,709 --> 00:37:30,334
Was he actually a teacher by profession, or did he teach in a mosque?

662
00:37:30,375 --> 00:37:31,959
Yes, he was a teacher

663
00:37:33,209 --> 00:37:36,000
He was a teacher and about 40 years old

664
00:37:37,375 --> 00:37:38,959
He had great knowledge of religion

665
00:37:40,209 --> 00:37:42,250
He asked us and encouraged us

666
00:37:43,167 --> 00:37:46,500
To memorize and read the Quran

667
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:50,500
Interviewer: What was the type of lessons exactly?

668
00:37:50,542 --> 00:37:56,042
Were the lessons related to jurisprudence and matters of purification, prayer, and creed?

669
00:37:56,042 --> 00:37:59,834
Or were there lessons you think they intended to push you to pledge allegiance?

670
00:37:59,876 --> 00:38:01,751
Were they advising you to pledge allegiance?

671
00:38:01,918 --> 00:38:06,500
And did they try to show you they were in the right, and so on?

672
00:38:06,500 --> 00:38:07,584
Was that the case?

673
00:38:07,584 --> 00:38:10,375
Yes, that's right—those things were there

674
00:38:10,918 --> 00:38:12,500
Interviewer: How so? What did they ask you, for example?

675
00:38:12,542 --> 00:38:13,959
And how did they deal with you on this matter?

676
00:38:15,542 --> 00:38:18,542
Honestly I don't know what to say to you

677
00:38:20,209 --> 00:38:21,959
Meaning they wanted us to join them

678
00:38:23,459 --> 00:38:25,584
Interviewer: Through the lessons?
Witness: Yes, through the lessons

679
00:38:26,459 --> 00:38:30,042
Interviewer: Through the lessons, did you receive an explicit call to pledge allegiance?

680
00:38:30,709 --> 00:38:33,250
Yes, they openly asked if anyone wanted to pledge allegiance

681
00:38:33,292 --> 00:38:34,751
Interviewer: Did a pledge of allegiance happen in the prison?

682
00:38:34,751 --> 00:38:38,709
No, during my 10 days there, that did not happen

683
00:38:40,083 --> 00:38:44,751
But young boys would come to Sheikh Shaban Mosque

684
00:38:45,042 --> 00:38:46,834
Which is Abu Dharr al-Ghifari Mosque

685
00:38:47,500 --> 00:38:53,209
They brought young children who didn't know anything

686
00:38:54,334 --> 00:38:58,167
They tricked them into pledging allegiance

687
00:38:59,751 --> 00:39:01,792
And brought them in to make them part of their members

688
00:39:02,250 --> 00:39:04,125
Interviewer: You mentioned the mosque is Sheikh Shaban Mosque

689
00:39:04,167 --> 00:39:05,500
Is its name Sheikh Shaban Mosque?

690
00:39:05,542 --> 00:39:08,250
No, its name is Abu Dharr al-Ghifari Mosque

691
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:14,667
But at that time there was a man named Sheikh Shaban in this mosque

692
00:39:14,918 --> 00:39:19,584
Interviewer: Do you mean they pledged allegiance with him?

693
00:39:19,584 --> 00:39:21,375
No, he was the one in charge of the mosque

694
00:39:22,125 --> 00:39:24,417
Interviewer: Who is this Sheikh Shaban?
Witness: He is from the local area

695
00:39:24,876 --> 00:39:25,918
Interviewer: Is he still around now?

696
00:39:26,250 --> 00:39:28,876
No, he isn't—he's in the north or in Turkey, I think

697
00:39:28,918 --> 00:39:31,042
Interviewer: Why is he in the north?
Witness: He hasn't come back

698
00:39:32,250 --> 00:39:34,500
He is one of their supporters

699
00:39:35,834 --> 00:39:37,834
Interviewer: Was he a supporter of ISIS?

700
00:39:38,083 --> 00:39:39,334
Yes, more or less a supporter

701
00:39:39,417 --> 00:39:43,250
Interviewer: Do you mean he went out there to escape?
Witness: Yes, he escaped

702
00:39:43,792 --> 00:39:45,500
Interviewer: His house and the money he had here, where did they go?

703
00:39:45,542 --> 00:39:47,209
I think they were confiscated

704
00:39:48,626 --> 00:39:52,125
Interviewer: Given that this man is from your area

705
00:39:52,292 --> 00:39:55,375
Did you know he supported ISIS, or did you find out after they came in?

706
00:39:55,417 --> 00:39:58,292
No, after they came in, he joined them out of fear

707
00:39:59,584 --> 00:40:01,334
Interviewer: And he is a religious man?
Witness: Yes, a religious man

708
00:40:02,834 --> 00:40:05,375
Interviewer: Did he really join them out of fear?

709
00:40:06,042 --> 00:40:07,626
ISIS are criminals

710
00:40:09,792 --> 00:40:10,959
Out of fear, anything can happen

711
00:40:11,500 --> 00:40:14,250
Interviewer: You were more afraid than him in prison, and you are not a religious man

712
00:40:14,292 --> 00:40:15,292
Why didn’t you join them?

713
00:40:15,334 --> 00:40:19,209
I would not join them, because I knew the government would return

714
00:40:19,792 --> 00:40:21,542
And that they would fall and the movie would end

715
00:40:23,918 --> 00:40:24,959
This group is manufactured

716
00:40:27,125 --> 00:40:31,125
Interviewer: Since you were with the group for 10 days

717
00:40:31,834 --> 00:40:34,459
And you said the food was the same and of the same kind

718
00:40:35,209 --> 00:40:39,459
Regarding your use of the bathrooms, since you were a large group

719
00:40:39,584 --> 00:40:41,667
How many toilets and showers were there?

720
00:40:41,709 --> 00:40:42,751
There was only one

721
00:40:42,834 --> 00:40:44,918
Interviewer: And you were more than 30 people?
Witness: Yes

722
00:40:44,959 --> 00:40:48,209
Interviewer: Was there any kind of schedule for going to the bathroom?

723
00:40:48,250 --> 00:40:50,334
Yes, it had to be quick in the morning

724
00:40:50,459 --> 00:40:53,876
Anyone who wanted to use the toilet had to hurry

725
00:40:53,959 --> 00:40:55,834
So the one behind him could go in

726
00:40:56,500 --> 00:40:58,292
Then the third, the fourth, and so on

727
00:40:58,417 --> 00:41:00,417
Interviewer: So it was up to you

728
00:41:00,459 --> 00:41:05,834
Yes, it was just a house, guarded by ISIS members

729
00:41:06,042 --> 00:41:08,918
But we were at ease, going to the toilet and so on

730
00:41:09,167 --> 00:41:11,792
Interviewer: Were cleaning supplies and soap available?

731
00:41:11,834 --> 00:41:13,167
Yes, they were available

732
00:41:13,459 --> 00:41:15,709
Interviewer: You were more than 30 people, so your number was large

733
00:41:15,792 --> 00:41:17,626
Did you have a cleaning schedule?

734
00:41:17,626 --> 00:41:19,417
Were two or three people cleaning daily?

735
00:41:19,459 --> 00:41:23,250
Yes, every day four people would clean a room

736
00:41:23,542 --> 00:41:24,834
There were two rooms

737
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:28,167
Interviewer: Were the four from the prisoners or from ISIS members?

738
00:41:28,209 --> 00:41:29,209
They were prisoners

739
00:41:29,250 --> 00:41:32,417
Interviewer: Did they set a schedule for you, or was it among you?

740
00:41:32,500 --> 00:41:35,709
Among ourselves, for example me and my friends

741
00:41:35,876 --> 00:41:38,542
We would be four, for example, and say we will do the cleaning today

742
00:41:39,542 --> 00:41:42,334
The next day, another four would do the cleaning

743
00:41:42,709 --> 00:41:47,584
They cleaned the sleeping area, swept, and wiped it with Dettol and a towel

744
00:41:48,959 --> 00:41:51,250
Interviewer: Were disinfectants also available?
Witness: Yes

745
00:41:51,417 --> 00:41:55,709
Interviewer: Did any prisoner develop a skin disease?

746
00:41:55,709 --> 00:41:59,334
No, that did not happen, because the period was short

747
00:42:00,334 --> 00:42:03,375
Interviewer: Did any prisoner suffer from a chronic illness?

748
00:42:03,500 --> 00:42:05,500
And did he have a special kind of food?

749
00:42:06,918 --> 00:42:09,959
A person who had a chronic illness, a heart condition, or other issues

750
00:42:10,209 --> 00:42:11,500
Had his medication with him

751
00:42:12,876 --> 00:42:16,542
Interviewer: And if his medicine ran out, would they bring him some?
Witness: Yes, they would give it to him

752
00:42:18,042 --> 00:42:20,167
Interviewer: Did it happen that someone asked them for treatment

753
00:42:20,209 --> 00:42:21,834
Interviewer: And did they tell him they didn’t have it?
Witness: No

754
00:42:22,334 --> 00:42:24,959
Interviewer: So if it was not available in the pharmacy, would they bring it from outside?

755
00:42:24,959 --> 00:42:28,000
Yes, they would bring it from outside

756
00:42:28,250 --> 00:42:31,459
Interviewer: You mentioned that the jailers’ treatment of you was normal

757
00:42:32,292 --> 00:42:35,918
Interviewer: Didn’t a judge come to you there?
Witness: They came for visits

758
00:42:36,375 --> 00:42:38,626
Interviewer: Did they come for interrogation?
Witness: No, they came for visits

759
00:42:39,250 --> 00:42:40,626
They would look over the place

760
00:42:41,667 --> 00:42:43,542
They called him <i>al-Hajji</i>, and we did not know who he was

761
00:42:43,667 --> 00:42:47,792
During that visit, was there direct contact and conversation with you as prisoners?

762
00:42:47,792 --> 00:42:50,584
Yes, they would ask us how the brothers treated us

763
00:42:50,918 --> 00:42:53,959
Meaning ISIS members, and we would tell him their treatment was good

764
00:42:56,417 --> 00:42:58,751
That was all, and we could not say more than that

765
00:42:59,834 --> 00:43:02,584
And even if their treatment was not good, we would say it was good

766
00:43:04,331 --> 00:43:06,667
Interviewer: Did torture or flogging happen there?
Witness: No, there was no torture

767
00:43:06,709 --> 00:43:08,042
Interviewer: Was there no flogging?
Witness: No

768
00:43:08,959 --> 00:43:11,209
Interviewer: And no one was punished there?
Witness: No

769
00:43:11,234 --> 00:43:12,834
Interviewer: Absolutely?
Witness: Yes, absolutely

770
00:43:12,876 --> 00:43:16,042
I told you we were comfortable

771
00:43:16,500 --> 00:43:17,626
Interviewer: How did they get you out of the prison?

772
00:43:18,167 --> 00:43:19,959
The course ended, so I left

773
00:43:20,542 --> 00:43:23,500
Interviewer: So they told you that when it ended, within 10 days, they would release you?

774
00:43:23,542 --> 00:43:25,167
Yes, when the course ends, we release you

775
00:43:25,209 --> 00:43:26,959
Interviewer: So they told you you would be out after 10 days?

776
00:43:27,042 --> 00:43:31,042
Yes, they said we had a course, and when it ends, they would release us

777
00:43:31,959 --> 00:43:34,042
So we counted the days

778
00:43:34,834 --> 00:43:36,959
Interviewer: While you were on the course

779
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:40,709
Did you get a visit from your family?

780
00:43:40,709 --> 00:43:41,876
No, I did not

781
00:43:41,959 --> 00:43:44,792
Interviewer: For you or for other prisoners?
Witness: No, visits were not allowed

782
00:43:49,292 --> 00:43:53,334
They released us at the time of the afternoon prayer

783
00:43:53,751 --> 00:43:56,209
They brought us to Hajj Idris Mosque

784
00:43:57,125 --> 00:43:58,626
Abd al-Rahman ibn Awf Mosque

785
00:43:58,709 --> 00:44:00,167
We went in and prayed the afternoon prayer

786
00:44:02,042 --> 00:44:03,459
And they released us from the mosque

787
00:44:05,375 --> 00:44:07,876
Interviewer: Did they treat you harshly?

788
00:44:07,918 --> 00:44:10,209
No, it was very ordinary treatment

789
00:44:10,250 --> 00:44:11,667
Interviewer: Where did you take your belongings from?

790
00:44:11,834 --> 00:44:14,459
They gave us the belongings there

791
00:44:14,500 --> 00:44:18,083
My watch, my things, and my ID, and we left

792
00:44:19,417 --> 00:44:24,083
Interviewer: After you got out and were released and returned home

793
00:44:24,125 --> 00:44:26,459
Did your family know you’d be released?

794
00:44:26,459 --> 00:44:27,459
No, they did not know

795
00:44:27,709 --> 00:44:29,959
Interviewer: Can you describe how you felt?

796
00:44:30,500 --> 00:44:34,542
And the moment your family met you, your wife and children?

797
00:44:34,626 --> 00:44:36,751
It was an indescribable feeling

798
00:44:37,375 --> 00:44:39,417
Interviewer: I want you to try to describe how it was

799
00:44:39,459 --> 00:44:43,626
I was very happy. I wanted to hug my children and my family

800
00:44:44,417 --> 00:44:46,209
And my friends and my people

801
00:44:46,417 --> 00:44:49,459
And they all celebrated me

802
00:44:50,167 --> 00:44:51,751
But it was a simple celebration

803
00:44:52,250 --> 00:44:54,334
So the noise would not be heard

804
00:44:54,375 --> 00:44:57,959
Because they were not allowed to hear the sounds of ululations and celebration

805
00:44:58,626 --> 00:45:00,000
Interviewer: How was your meeting with your wife?

806
00:45:00,042 --> 00:45:01,959
And with your mother who was still alive at the time?

807
00:45:02,667 --> 00:45:07,584
How did you feel in that meeting and was there crying from joy?

808
00:45:08,083 --> 00:45:09,125
Yes, there was crying from joy

809
00:45:10,167 --> 00:45:13,042
My kids and my wife cried from joy

810
00:45:15,042 --> 00:45:19,125
And they asked me at home—What did you do for them to take you?

811
00:45:19,500 --> 00:45:23,918
I told them, I did nothing, you are my family and you know what I have

812
00:45:24,500 --> 00:45:25,792
They took me unjustly

813
00:45:26,334 --> 00:45:29,375
And thank God, God made it easy for me and I was released

814
00:45:33,959 --> 00:45:36,417
Interviewer: After you stayed 38 days

815
00:45:36,876 --> 00:45:40,417
Of which 28 days were in solitary and alone

816
00:45:40,500 --> 00:45:42,500
And that was the hardest period you went through

817
00:45:42,584 --> 00:45:43,626
Yes, it was

818
00:45:45,667 --> 00:45:49,250
Interviewer: How did you become after this experience?

819
00:45:49,667 --> 00:45:54,250
Was your life after release the same as it was before prison?

820
00:45:54,375 --> 00:45:57,292
Was your personality the same before and after prison?

821
00:45:57,334 --> 00:45:58,918
Or did your life change?

822
00:46:02,500 --> 00:46:04,834
I became cautious in everything

823
00:46:05,626 --> 00:46:08,667
In my movements, in my words, in everything

824
00:46:09,959 --> 00:46:13,542
I even started praying right on time

825
00:46:14,792 --> 00:46:16,209
When the muezzin says Allahu Akbar

826
00:46:16,250 --> 00:46:19,834
I go straight to the mosque, because of fear

827
00:46:21,709 --> 00:46:25,751
Interviewer: Did you have psychological changes?

828
00:46:25,834 --> 00:46:29,209
For example, you were not quick to anger before

829
00:46:29,250 --> 00:46:31,167
Did you become quick to anger?

830
00:46:31,209 --> 00:46:34,500
I had a psychological problem and because of it I still see a psychiatrist

831
00:46:34,584 --> 00:46:36,167
His name is Dr. Ali Neamat

832
00:46:37,125 --> 00:46:38,918
Interviewer: Because of this detention?
Witness: Yes, because of it

833
00:46:38,959 --> 00:46:41,584
And until now I take psychiatric medication

834
00:46:42,042 --> 00:46:43,876
Interviewer: How was your condition at the beginning?

835
00:46:43,959 --> 00:46:45,918
Surely your condition now is not like it was at the beginning

836
00:46:46,083 --> 00:46:47,500
So how was your condition at the beginning?

837
00:46:47,500 --> 00:46:53,918
Did you feel that your interactions were easy with your wife, children, and people?

838
00:46:54,209 --> 00:46:58,167
Or were you withdrawn and afraid of everyone?

839
00:46:58,459 --> 00:47:02,375
Did you become more afraid for your children, that the same thing might happen to them?

840
00:47:02,417 --> 00:47:04,125
I want you to describe that state you were in

841
00:47:04,209 --> 00:47:09,292
Before prison I was normal and had no problem

842
00:47:09,751 --> 00:47:12,959
But after prison I developed this psychological problem

843
00:47:14,167 --> 00:47:18,667
I was irritable with my family, my wife, and my kids

844
00:47:19,876 --> 00:47:24,500
And when ISIS was present my anger was mixed with fear

845
00:47:24,584 --> 00:47:27,584
I feared that if I raised my voice they would hear it, because they walked right by the door

846
00:47:28,500 --> 00:47:29,959
Interviewer: Did you feel you were being watched?

847
00:47:30,626 --> 00:47:31,792
Yes, I felt I was being watched

848
00:47:32,417 --> 00:47:35,542
Interviewer: Were you not comfortable with your actions and movements even in your home?

849
00:47:35,959 --> 00:47:38,000
Yes, because I developed a psychological problem

850
00:47:38,542 --> 00:47:40,751
A severe psychological problem until now

851
00:47:41,125 --> 00:47:48,876
Interviewer: Your relationships with people, trust in them, and new relationships

852
00:47:48,959 --> 00:47:52,500
Were they the same as they used to be?

853
00:47:52,626 --> 00:47:56,417
In making decisions with people or with a specific person

854
00:47:56,834 --> 00:48:00,959
Was it the same thinking and same feeling?

855
00:48:01,334 --> 00:48:03,000
No, I’ve become different now

856
00:48:03,209 --> 00:48:04,209
Interviewer: What do you mean by different?

857
00:48:04,250 --> 00:48:06,918
I’ve become afraid of people

858
00:48:07,542 --> 00:48:13,042
I speak cautiously, and the words I say I must be certain of

859
00:48:13,456 --> 00:48:15,918
Interviewer: And that continued even after ISIS left?
Witness: Yes, until now

860
00:48:16,143 --> 00:48:18,125
Interviewer: And is it the same with your relationships with people?

861
00:48:18,626 --> 00:48:23,417
My relationships are just greetings and I don’t like to get close with anyone

862
00:48:23,459 --> 00:48:25,417
I’ve become quiet

863
00:48:26,667 --> 00:48:29,417
Interviewer: Is this all just a reaction?
Witness: Yes, it is

864
00:48:29,918 --> 00:48:31,542
Interviewer: And can you get rid of it?

865
00:48:31,959 --> 00:48:34,167
I ask God to let me get rid of it

866
00:48:34,417 --> 00:48:35,542
Interviewer: God willing

867
00:48:38,167 --> 00:48:41,292
Interviewer: Do you want to tell us a particular story or incident?

868
00:48:42,709 --> 00:48:46,667
That happened to you while you were in prison or while ISIS was in Mosul

869
00:48:47,959 --> 00:48:50,918
Or an image you recall now before you

870
00:48:51,167 --> 00:48:54,959
Or an incident that affected you or made you cry under ISIS

871
00:48:55,500 --> 00:48:58,000
Something that happened in front of you and made you sad and cry

872
00:48:58,876 --> 00:49:01,918
I was saddened for the people who died

873
00:49:03,209 --> 00:49:05,417
I was saddened for my house that was looted

874
00:49:06,918 --> 00:49:09,042
And I had nothing else

875
00:49:10,751 --> 00:49:12,459
And after the area was liberated

876
00:49:12,542 --> 00:49:14,626
Good people came and helped us

877
00:49:15,626 --> 00:49:17,209
One brought me a fridge to help

878
00:49:17,209 --> 00:49:20,417
Another brought me a freezer, another brought me a sofa set

879
00:49:20,918 --> 00:49:23,417
I’d lost everything I owned

880
00:49:25,751 --> 00:49:29,876
And until now I rent a house, I don’t own one

881
00:49:32,375 --> 00:49:35,792
And the government has not compensated me for anything

882
00:49:36,626 --> 00:49:39,292
We’ve given up on the existing government, we’ve lost hope in them

883
00:49:39,918 --> 00:49:41,334
And thank God, Lord of the worlds

884
00:49:41,709 --> 00:49:44,667
Interviewer: You said you were saddened for your looted house

885
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:47,667
Was it looted by ISIS?

886
00:49:47,959 --> 00:49:50,459
Or did it happen during the battle?

887
00:49:50,667 --> 00:49:52,459
Or was it looted by certain people?

888
00:49:52,542 --> 00:49:55,292
How was it looted, and who did it?

889
00:49:55,626 --> 00:49:57,417
The looting that happened

890
00:49:57,792 --> 00:50:02,626
Was by ISIS and by gangs during the liberation

891
00:50:04,542 --> 00:50:06,375
And my house was destroyed by shelling

892
00:50:08,125 --> 00:50:09,125
And there was looting

893
00:50:11,042 --> 00:50:14,959
Like the Ali Baba gangs and other thieves

894
00:50:15,167 --> 00:50:17,459
Interviewer: Were those who looted from Mosul?

895
00:50:17,626 --> 00:50:20,459
No, they were strangers

896
00:50:21,125 --> 00:50:23,876
Interviewer: Do you mean strangers from Mosul’s outskirts or from outside?

897
00:50:24,250 --> 00:50:25,959
From gangs that entered Mosul?

898
00:50:28,792 --> 00:50:31,918
The gangs that entered Mosul are the ones who destroyed it

899
00:50:32,584 --> 00:50:34,167
The people of Mosul did not destroy it

900
00:50:34,709 --> 00:50:38,417
Interviewer: You personally, aside from the money stolen from your house

901
00:50:38,459 --> 00:50:40,751
And the things stolen from it, and aside from prison

902
00:50:42,834 --> 00:50:45,292
What do you feel was stolen from you besides these?

903
00:50:48,292 --> 00:50:49,375
My health was stolen

904
00:50:51,334 --> 00:50:57,083
When I lost my health I lost the dearest thing I had

905
00:50:59,250 --> 00:51:01,918
And I could no longer make my family live properly

906
00:51:03,209 --> 00:51:04,626
Because there is no livelihood

907
00:51:05,918 --> 00:51:07,292
And no work like before

908
00:51:09,292 --> 00:51:15,709
Now they give me a small welfare salary, it doesn’t even cover the rent

909
00:51:18,959 --> 00:51:20,375
And our hope is in God

910
00:51:21,209 --> 00:51:23,167
Interviewer: How do you make money besides welfare now?

911
00:51:23,167 --> 00:51:24,167
I can’t work

912
00:51:24,292 --> 00:51:26,125
Interviewer: And your kids?
Witness: They are young

913
00:51:28,876 --> 00:51:29,959
They go to school

914
00:51:31,209 --> 00:51:34,250
I pulled my eldest son out of school so he could work and support me

915
00:51:35,626 --> 00:51:36,751
He is 17 years old
